text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Linguistic Discrimination of SAE%0a:Author: chester_g%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 09:21%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-192337-841490#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:23-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-192337-841490#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aComedian Jeff Foxworthy notes the bias often felt with his Southern accent.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IyLVE3BZ-V4&ab_channel=JeffFoxworthy-Topic%0a%0aAlthough the Southern American English dialect accounts for one of the largest regions in American English, it still faces its fair share of criticism. Like other dialects of Standardized American English, the dialect is often considered unprofessional. Like Foxworthy mentions, most Americans would immaturely judge a doctor if they had his southern accent. This is a perfect example of a designated "professional" language, and a reason why discrimination in the work place is extremely prevalent. %0a%0aSimilarly to workplace discrimination, Foxworthy notes the consistency that Standardized American English speakers designate the Southern American accent as less intelligent. This includes the simplication of word terminators like [ŋ] to [n] and vowel dipthong shifts. This shortening of words and shifting of vowels is the main subject of discrimination in SAE. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
